Support for C14N 1.1 has been integrated. C14N 1.1 is now a proposed recommendation (http://www.w3.org/TR/2008/PR-xml-c14n11-20080129/). From
the Introduction : 

"Canonical XML 1.1 is a revision to Canonical XML 1.0 to address issues related to inheritance of attributes in the XML namespace when canonicalizing document subsets, including the requirement not to inherit xml:id, and to treat xml:base URI path processing properly."

You can specify C14N 1.1 as a CanonicalizationMethod or Transform algorithm as
follows:

JSR 105 API:

  XMLSignatureFactory fac = XMLSignatureFactory.getInstance("DOM");
  CanonicalizationMethod cm = 
    fac.newCanonicalizationMethod
      ("http://www.w3.org/2006/12/xml-c14n11", (C14NMethodParameterSpec) null);
  Transform transform = 
    fac.newTransform
      ("http://www.w3.org/2006/12/xml-c14n11", (TransformParameterSpec) null);
  // or "http://www.w3.org/2006/12/xml-c14n11#WithComments" to preserve comments

XMLSec API:

  XMLSignature sig = 
    new XMLSignature(doc, baseURI, Canonicalizer.ALGO_ID_C14N11_OMIT_COMMENTS);
  // or Canonicalizer.ALGO_ID_C14N11_WITH_COMMENTS to preserve comments
  Transforms transforms = new Transforms(doc);
  transforms.addTransform(Transforms.TRANSFORM_C14N11_OMIT_COMMENTS);
  // or TRANSFORM_C14N_WITH_COMMENTS to preserve comments

Also, if you would like an explicit C14N 1.1 Transform to be added to your Reference when necessary (see section 3.1 of the XML Signature Second Edition draft: http://www.w3.org/2007/xmlsec/Drafts/xmldsig-core/#sec-CoreGeneration)
then you need to enable the following system property:

org.apache.xml.security.useC14N11=true

At some point in the future, we should make this the default, but not until there is more support for C14N 1.1 in XML Signature implementations.
